body:
## Motivation

See #749.

Support for `eth_call` state [overrides](https://geth.ethereum.org/docs/rpc/ns-eth#3-object---state-override-set).

## Solution

Adds a `Provider::call_builder()` method, which returns a `Caller` struct. This `Caller` implements `Future`, so it can be `.await`ed the same way the async `call()` method is now. Additionally, it provides builder methods to set the block number and state overrides.

This might be useful as-is, but I think the ultimate goal would be to have what is currently named `call_builder()` replace the `Middleware::call()` method. It seems like this will require some signficant refactoring in addition to a breaking change, though.

Naming is all up for grabs, though "override" is a reserved keyword, which is the reason for the current choice of "spoof".

## Example

```rust
use ethers_core::{
    types::{Address, TransactionRequest, H256},
    utils::{parse_ether},
};
use ethers_providers::{Provider, Http, Middleware, spoof};
use std::convert::TryFrom;

let provider = Provider::<Http>::try_from("http://127.0.0.1:8545").unwrap();

let adr1: Address = "0x6fC21092DA55B392b045eD78F4732bff3C580e2c".parse().unwrap();
let adr2: Address = "0x295a70b2de5e3953354a6a8344e616ed314d7251".parse().unwrap();
let pay_amt = parse_ether(1u64)?;

// Not enough ether to pay for the transaction
let tx = TransactionRequest::pay(adr2, pay_amt).from(adr1).into();

// would fail (insufficient balance)
provider.call_builder(&tx).await.unwrap();

// override storage, nonce, etc. with the call
let mut state = spoof::state();
state
    .account(adr1)
    .store(H256::default(), 1.into())
    .nonce(2.into())
    .balance(pay_amt * 2);
provider.call_builder(&tx).block(100.into()).spoof(&state).await.unwrap();

// override just the balance
let state = spoof::balance(adr1, pay_amt * 2);
provider.call_builder(&tx).spoof(&state).await.unwrap();
```
 

